About

This paper contains an analysis about Human Rights Scores (HRS) and its relationship with air pollution. The data used can be found in Human rights and Outdoor air pollution pages by Our World In Data. Images used by Mika Baumeister and Zoya Loonohod in Unsplash.

This work has no lucrative intentions of any kind, only interest in understanding and knowing. If you can contribute with more information for this work, you can contact me through any of these links

Introduction

The relationship between human rights violations and air pollution because of industrialization is not very clear yet. From one perspective, we need to redefine the way we measure human rights scores, because of the recognition of new dimensions these rights can be violated (Roser, 2016) and the measure standards of several organizations (Fariss, 2014).

Roser (2016)

On the other hand, the way air pollution reflects on the health and economy of a country can be measured in number of deaths. Outdoor air pollution was the 6th cause of death in 2017 accross all ages and both sexes (Stanaway et al., 2018).

Ritchie and Roser (2019)

Also, most emissions occur in North Africa and South Asia (Ritchie and Roser, 2019)

Ritchie and Roser (2019)

Labor overexploitation in the industrial sector among countries can be, for example, one of the dimensions human rights can be violated. In addition, safety protocols and bioethics play a crucial role at preventing an increase in deaths and human rights violations.

Methods

We are going to analyze the data of 184 countries to look for relationships in HRS and air pollution. We will use simple descriptive statistics and compare HRS levels and air pollution concentrations with ANOVA to look for differences in distributions in these levels, with its consequent Tukey-Kramer test to see where these differences lie in.

Load data

First, we start by loading the libraries we are going to need.

# Load libraries

# Load data

Now theres 184 countries for the new datasets created for 2016. We will take the air pollution values from ap_2016 and add them to hrs_2016, create a factor for countries and arrange them from highest score to lowest score.

# Add air pollution variable to hrs_2016
hrs_2016$air.poll.mean <- ap_2016$air.poll.mean

# Rearrange countries by human rights score
hrs_2016 <- hrs_2016 %>%
  arrange(-score)

# Create a factor of countries
hrs_2016$entity <- factor(hrs_2016$entity, levels = hrs_2016$entity)

Correlation

According to the last information, we plot the graphs for the air pollution in the 10 highest and lowest HRS countries and the scatteplot correlation.

In general, for highest HRS countries theres a lower abundance in air contamination than for lowest HRS countries. We see this same trend in the scatterplot (a higher HRS generally implies a lower air pollution). Nonetheless, we see countries with deficiency in human rights but with their air pollution in lowest levels, maybe because of lack of resources and/or industrialization.

Evolution by year

Now, we are interested in plotting the evolution of HRS and air pollution year by year.

Theres an upward trend for HRS worldwide (fortunately), but we cant say the same for air pollution in the last 26 years as it almost follows this same tendency.

Back to 2016

Distribution of air pollution by HRS level

We are going to make a nominal variable for HRS at 5 different levels: Very low, Low, Mid, High and Very high. Next, we will see the summary for all them.

# Make nominal variable for HRS
hrs_2016$score_name <- cut(
  hrs_2016$score,
  breaks = 5,
  labels = c('Very low', 'Low', 'Mid', 'High', 'Very high'),
  include.lowest = T)

# Summary by score name
by(hrs_2016, hrs_2016['score_name'], summary)

Its clearer now that for air.poll.mean the higher the level of HRS, the lower the air pollution concentration.

ANOVA

We are going to make the hypothesis testing that at least one level differs from the others (alternative) in contrast to the hypothesis that all distributions all the same (null) at the level of 0.05.

# ANOVA
anova_mod <- lm(air.poll.mean ~ score_name, hrs_2016)
anova(anova_mod)
## Analysis of Variance Table
##
## Response: air.poll.mean
##             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value    Pr(>F)
## score_name   4  41194 10298.5  11.111 4.505e-08 ***
## Residuals  179 165904   926.8
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

As p-value << 0.05, we conclude theres at least one difference. What this indicates is a possible correlation between HRS and air pollution. As illustrated in the graph, countries with a high HRS remain low in particulate matter emissions in contrast to low HRS countries.

We will see these differences in more detail with a Tukey-Kramer post-hoc test.

Most differences lie between Very low with Mid, High and Very high levels. Also, between Low and Mid, High and Very high levels. This indicates that Very low and Low HRS levels, as we suspect, got higher particulate matter concentration in emissions to the atmosphere.

Conclusions

Highest HRS countries tend to have the lowest air pollution concentration in comparison with lowest HRS countries. The distribution in concentration for these levels also gets wider meanwhile decreasing in HRS levels.

Increase in HRS in the last years not necessarily indicate that emissions will decrease immediately, as this depends more in successive transition to other kinds of energy applied by economical politics and the interest of citizenship.
